<article>
    <h1>2&#xD;&#xA;THE ALIEN FRAN&#xAD;CHISE</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200920/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-20"><time>2020-09-20</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | FEATURES</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>It is a shame that the first and third films in the science-fic­tion thriller se­ries, which has four in­stal­ments, are miss­ing on Net­flix, but what is avail­able still makes for fairly solid view­ing.</p>
    <p>Sigour­ney Weaver’s Ellen Ri­p­ley be­comes one of the great­est re­luc­tant he­roes in movie his­tory in the fran­chise.</p>
    <p>The sec­ond in­stal­ment, Aliens (1986), is di­rec­tor James Cameron’s “war in space” an­swer to Ri­d­ley Scott’s “haunted house in space” idea for Alien, the first movie in 1979.</p>
    <p>Scott re­turned to make the am­bi­tious pre­quel, Prometheus (2012), telling view­ers that to un­der­stand where the Alien came from, you have to know where life on Earth orig­i­nated.</p>
    <p>Alien Res­ur­rec­tion (1997) came af­ter the mis­fire that was Alien 3 (1992). A re­turn to the ac­tion and hor­ror ideas that made the sec­ond movie a hit, it was to be the last time fans would see the Ri­p­ley char­ac­ter that Weaver made so mem­o­rable.</p>
    <p>Two spin-offs, Alien Vs Preda­tor (2004) and its 2007 se­quel, which pit the two movie mon­sters in com­bat, are here for bonus points.</p>
    <p>Watch on Net­flix:</p>
    <p>Aliens (1986)</p>
    <p>Alien Res­ur­rec­tion (1997) Prometheus (2012)</p>
    <p>Alien Vs Preda­tor (2004)</p>
    <p>Alien Vs Preda­tor: Re­quiem (2007)</p>

